Ringgit Gains Most in a Month on Growth Optimism; Bonds Steady

-- B y   D a v i d   Y o n g
-- 
2011-03-01T09:08:29Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-01/ringgit-advances-for-third-day-on-u-s-china-growth-optimism.html
Malaysia’s ringgit rallied the most
in a month as economic news from  China  and the U.S. brightened
the outlook for exports.  The currency advanced for a third day to near a 13-year
high after an index showed China’s manufacturing industry
continued to expand in January and by more than forecast in a
Bloomberg poll. A separate manufacturing gauge in the U.S. is
expected to have risen last month to the highest level since May
24, according to economists surveyed by Bloomberg.  Bonds were steady. Overseas investors boosted their
holdings of local-currency debt by 7 percent during January to a
record,  Bank Negara Malaysia  said late yesterday.  “The economic data provides some support for the market
and we see sustained confidence among foreign investors in the
ringgit,” said Mohd. Yazid Safuan, head of treasury sales and
trading at Al Rajhi Banking & Investment Corp. in  Kuala Lumpur .
“People are not prepared to short the dollar in a big way,
given the political tension in the Middle East.”  The ringgit rose 0.4 percent to 3.0370 per dollar as of
4:25 p.m. in Kuala Lumpur, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg. It strengthened 0.4 percent last month and reached
3.0240 on Feb. 21, the strongest level since October 1997.  Overseas investors owned 129.2 billion ringgit ($42
billion) of local currency-denominated debt at the end of
January, Bank Negara Malaysia said on its website late
yesterday, 76 percent higher than the total a year earlier.  The  Institute for Supply Management ’s manufacturing index
rose to 61 in February, from 60.8 in January, according to the
median estimate of economists in a Bloomberg News survey before
the data due today. Readings greater than 50 signal growth.  Bonds Steady  China’s Purchasing Managers Index was at 52.2 in February
versus 52.9 in January, according to the National Bureau of
Statistics and Federation of Logistics and Purchasing. The
median forecast of economists in a Bloomberg survey was for a
reading of 52.1.  Five-year  government bonds  were steady, keeping yields at a
two-week low, after government reports shows inflation in
Southeast Asia’s two biggest economies eased in February.  The yield on 3.835 percent bond maturing in August 2015
held at 3.41 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The price was
little-changed after rising yesterday by the most since Feb. 10.  Consumer prices in  Indonesia  rose 6.84 percent last month
from a year earlier, versus 7.02 percent in January. The pace in  Thailand  slowed to 2.87 percent from 3.03 percent. Malaysia will
report its February data on March 23.  To contact the reporter on this story:
David Yong in  Singapore  at 
 dyong@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:  James Regan  at 
 jregan19@bloomberg.net . 